    ],
    "explanation": "'When you arrive at the station, I'll call you right away': Quando arriverai alla stazione, ti chiamerò subito. Where English uses the present after 'when' ('when you arrive'), Italian puts BOTH verbs in the future: the arriving is still to come, so it takes 'arriverai', not the present 'arrivi'. After quando pointing at a future moment, Italian keeps the future throughout.",
    "examiner_note": "Two markpoints per Rev 27: the temporal-subordinate USAGE and the future-vs-present CONTRAST both fire full on 'arriverai', 0.5 each. Suppressed and carries candidate_tenses (criterion 16). 'arrivi' (the English-style present) is the wrong-tense catch on both markpoints.",
