    "explanation": "'As soon as I finish work, I'll let you know': Appena finirò di lavorare, ti farò sapere. English says 'as soon as I finish' with a present, but Italian uses the future after 'appena' when the action is still to come: 'appena finirò'. The present 'finisco' would be the English pattern carried over wrongly.",
